:["English (East Anglia): from the Middle English personal name <i>Stanhard</i> (Old English <i>Stānheard</i>, from <i>stān</i> ‘stone’ + <i>heard</i> ‘hard, bold’)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Maud Stonard Stonard Of Cornwall was born in 1365, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Stonard, was 25 and her mother, Joan Verch Stonard John Ap Cwthi, was 23. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Ralph Kayl II. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1365–":"1365–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1385–1455":"1385–1455","–Male":"Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1342–Female":"1342–Surnud","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, Unite